âœ… Part 2: Control Flow & Loops â€“ Deep Dive

ğŸ”¹ Topic: if, else, switch, and Loops

Q1. What is the difference between if-else and switch statements?
ğŸ”¸ if-else:
Used when conditions are based on expressions or ranges.

let age = 20;

if (age < 13) {
  console.log("Child");
} else if (age < 18) {
  console.log("Teen");
} else {
  console.log("Adult");
}
ğŸ”¸ switch:
Better for discrete values (not ranges).

let color = "blue";

switch (color) {
  case "red":
    console.log("Red");
    break;
  case "blue":
    console.log("Blue");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Unknown");
}

ğŸ” Use Case Comparison:

Case	Use if-else	Use switch

Ranges/complex logic	âœ…	âŒ

Exact matches	âœ…	âœ…

Better readability	âŒ (with many conditions)	âœ…

Q2. What is the difference between while, do...while, and for loops?

Loop Type	When Condition Is Checked	Runs Minimum Once?
for	Before each iteration	No
while	Before each iteration	No
do...while	After each iteration	âœ… Yes

âœ… Examples:

// for
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  console.log(i); // 0 1 2
}

// while
let j = 0;
while (j < 3) {
  console.log(j); // 0 1 2
  j++;
}

// do...while
let k = 0;
do {
  console.log(k); // 0 1 2
  k++;
} while (k < 3);

Q3. What is the difference between for...in and for...of loops?
ğŸ”¹ for...in: Iterates over keys (object properties or array indices)
ğŸ”¹ for...of: Iterates over values (only iterable objects like arrays, strings)

const arr = ['a', 'b', 'c'];

for (let index in arr) {
  console.log(index); // "0", "1", "2"
}

for (let value of arr) {
  console.log(value); // "a", "b", "c"
}
âŒ for...of doesnâ€™t work on plain objects:

const obj = { a: 1, b: 2 };
for (let key of obj) { } // âŒ TypeError: obj is not iterable

Q4. How do break and continue work in loops?
break: Exits the loop entirely.

continue: Skips to the next iteration.

for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  if (i === 2) continue;
  if (i === 4) break;
  console.log(i); // 0 1 3
}

Q5. Real-world Scenario Question:
â€œGiven a number n, print all even numbers less than n, but skip numbers divisible by 4.â€

function printEvens(n) {
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    if (i % 2 !== 0) continue;
    if (i % 4 === 0) continue;
    console.log(i);
  }
}
printEvens(10); // Output: 2, 6, 10

Q6. How do labeled statements work in JavaScript?
Used with break or continue to break nested loops.

outerLoop: for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    if (i === j) break outerLoop;
    console.log(i, j);
  }
}

âœ… Summary Cheatsheet:

Keyword	Purpose

if	Conditional branching

switch	Multi-way branching based on exact value

for	Definite loop with counter

while	Loop with condition

do...while	Loop at least once

break	Exit loop immediately

continue	Skip current iteration

for...in	Loop through keys of object

for...of	Loop through values of iterable

