âœ… Part 7: Asynchronous JavaScript â€“ setTimeout, Event Loop, Promises, async/await

ğŸ”¹ Q1. What is Asynchronous JavaScript?
JavaScript is single-threaded, but it can perform asynchronous tasks (like fetching data, waiting, etc.) without blocking the main thread. This is possible through:

Event Loop

Callback Queue

Promises

Web APIs (browser)

ğŸ”¹ Q2. What is setTimeout() and how does it work?
âœ… Example:

console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Timeout");
}, 0);

console.log("End");
ğŸ” Output:
sql

Start
End
Timeout
Even with 0 ms, the callback is placed in the Callback Queue and executed after the current stack is empty.

ğŸ”¹ Q3. What is the Event Loop in JavaScript?
ğŸ”¸ Answer:
The event loop constantly checks the call stack and callback queue. If the call stack is empty, it pushes the first task from the queue into the stack.

âœ… Visual:

[Stack Empty] --> Event Loop --> Move callbacks from queue â†’ stack â†’ run

ğŸ”¹ Q4. What is a Promise in JavaScript?
A Promise represents a value that may be available now, later, or never.


const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  let success = true;
  if (success) resolve("Done");
  else reject("Failed");
});

promise
  .then((res) => console.log(res))
  .catch((err) => console.log(err));

ğŸ”¹ Q5. Promise States
State	Description
Pending	Initial state
Fulfilled	resolve() was called
Rejected	reject() was called

ğŸ”¹ Q6. Chaining Promises

doWork()
  .then((res1) => {
    return doMore(res1);
  })
  .then((res2) => {
    return finish(res2);
  })
  .catch((err) => console.log("Error:", err));

ğŸ”¹ Q7. What is async/await in JavaScript?
async and await are syntactic sugar over Promises to write asynchronous code like synchronous code.

âœ… Example:

async function fetchData() {
  try {
    let res = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
    let data = await res.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (err) {
    console.log("Error:", err);
  }
}
fetchData();

ğŸ”¹ Q8. Interview Trap: Whatâ€™s the output?

console.log("1");

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("2");
}, 0);

Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log("3"));

console.log("4");
âœ… Output:

1
4
3
2
ğŸ” Why?
setTimeout â†’ goes to Web APIs â†’ Callback Queue

Promise.then â†’ goes to Microtask Queue, runs before timeout

ğŸ”¹ Q9. Real-world Interview Task: Simulate an API call

function fakeFetch(url) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve(`Data from ${url}`);
    }, 1000);
  });
}

async function getData() {
  const data = await fakeFetch("https://api.example.com");
  console.log(data);
}

getData(); // After 1s: Data from https://api.example.com

